revision.text:
In the 18th and 19th centuries, a '''bear-leader''' was a [[colloquialism]] for a man who escorted young men of rank or wealth on their travels, such as young [[gentlemen]] on the [[Grand Tour]].  The role of bear-leader blended elements of [[tutor]], [[Legal guardian|guardian]], [[Chaperone (social)|chaperon]] and companion.  A late example in literature can be seen in the ambitious Oxford tutor hired to keep an increasingly alcoholic young man out of harm's way – and out of the way – in ''[[Brideshead Revisited]]''.

