{{Infobox writer | name = Margaret Wynne Lawless | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = MARGARET WYNNE LAWLESS A woman of the century (page 462 crop).jpg | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = "A woman of the century" | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = Margaret Wynne | birth_date = July 14, 1847 | birth_place = [[Adrian, Michigan]], U.S. | death_date = {{dda|1926|1|18|1847|7|14}} | death_place = [[Toledo, Ohio]], U.S. | resting_place = Calvary Cemetery, Toledo | occupation = poet, author, educator, philanthropist | language = English | residence = | nationality = American | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = [[Adrian High School (Michigan)|Adrian High School]] | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = {{marriage|James Thomas Lawless|1873}} | partner = | children = 8 | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} --> | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }} '''Margaret Wynne Lawless''' (July 14, 1847 – January 18, 1926) was an American poet, author, educator, and philanthropist. She contributed to the ''[[Catholic World]]'', ''[[Ave Maria Press|Ave Maria]]'', ''Rosary Magazine'', ''Pilot'', ''[[The New World (newspaper)|New World]]'', and conducted the children's department for a number of years of the ''Catholic Universe''. Lawless also contributed to ''[[Frank Leslie's Illustrated Newspaper]]'', ''[[William Jennings Demorest|Demorest Monthly Magazine]]'', ''[[The American Magazine]]'', ''[[Lippincott's Monthly Magazine]]'', ''[[Golden Days for Boys and Girls]]'', ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' and ''Travelers' Record''. She was active in the cause of Catholic education and the development of Catholic charitable, literary and socialistic societies and institutions. Lawless incorporated and took out a charter for the Catholic Ladies of [[Ohio]], the first insurance and benevolent society for women in the United States.{{sfn|Logan|1912|p=836}}
==Early years== Margaret Wynne was born in [[Adrian, Michigan]], July 14, 1847. She was a daughter of John and Jane Meehan Wynne,{{sfn|Logan|1912|p=836}} both Irish Catholics.{{sfn|Curtis|Elder|1911|p=359}} She passed her childhood and youth in Adrian.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=452}}
She was educated in the public schools of Adrian, receiving in the [[Adrian High School (Michigan)|Adrian High School]] a full collegiate classical and mathematical course modeled after the Amherat plan, attaining at an early age great proficiency, especially in the classics, Latin and Greek, and graduating when fourteen years old.{{sfn|Curtis|Elder|1911|p=359}} Up to that time, she had shown no especial literary taste, but when she went back to her alma mater to take a post-graduate course, she intermingled with her studies a rhymed translation of the first of the ''[[Satires (Horace)|Satires]] of [[Horace]]''.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=452}}
==Career== After graduating from school she taught for several years.{{sfn|Logan|1912|p=836}} In 1873, she married Dr. James Thomas Lawless (1844–1932), a practicing physician in [[Toledo, Ohio]]. They made their home in Toledo, and had eight sons.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=452}}
She began writing poetry in 1886,{{sfn|Curtis|Elder|1911|p=359}} sending poems and fiction to [[Eastern United States|eastern]] magazines, where they found ready acceptance and fair remuneration. A few years passed away, and then a nearly mortal illness forced her to give up writing, as she supposed, forever.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=452}}
After several years of raising a family, she again set forth her work as a writer, this time with a clearer perception of the meaning of life, with a better understanding of her own powers, and with higher purposes. Before, she wrote for the mere pleasure of writing, with her later writings there was a message for her to deliver, and it came most readily and clearly in lines glowing with poetic fervor.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=452}}
Lawless was not a prolific writer, but her name was not a stranger in many of the leading magazines and papers of the country in her time, such as ''The Catholic World'', ''Ave Maria'', ''Rosary Magazine'', ''Pilot'', ''New World'', ''Catholic Universe'' (of which she conducted the Children's Dept. for a number of years), as well as to the following secular publications, ''Our Youth'', ''Frank Leslie's Weekly'', ''Weekly Wisconsin'', ''Demorest's'', ''American Magazine'', ''Lippincott's'', ''Golden Days'', ''Detroit Free Press'', and ''Traveler's Record''. She never published a book of her poems, but was engaged in compiling her writings with that end in view.{{sfn|Curtis|Elder|1911|p=359}}{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=452}} Both she and her husband were active workers in the cause of Catholic education and the development of Catholic charitable, literary and socialistic societies and institutions. Lawless incorporated and took out a charter for the Catholic Ladies of Ohio, the first insurance and benevolent society for women in the United States, and was for six years secretary of this organization.{{sfn|Logan|1912|p=836}}
Lawless died January 18, 1926, in Toledo, and was buried in that town's Calvary Cemetery.
